{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c978028-ac56-4bc4-bad1-5d4c6e455745","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName); // optional: verify details\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`)\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pins the exception to the exact call\n- You can inspect the exception (message, inner exception, etc.)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"46748cda-02aa-49f1-b0fc-80b9da7e68f9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no need to explore a codebase.","outputTokens":257,"requestId":"A043:834FC:CEB1A6:F37C2E:69FE8DAC"},"id":"1332ecc1-122b-4786-a0fb-9a32e8f5976f","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:28:19.122Z","parentId":"a4100682-e679-4c3d-b4ca-2a3ac0b65e1c"}
